surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FG030936%2F1"><gtr:id>07993B7A-D27F-4C9D-A8A0-18D683C843AF</gtr:id><gtr:title>Postdoctoral Fellowship Application</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G030936/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Scientific study into the origins and evolution of natural language has undergone something of a renaissance in the past 20 years.&amp;nbsp; Dr. Scott-Phillips's PhD. examined human communication from the perspective of social evolution theory - the subdiscipline of biology that is concerned with the social behaviour of organisms, particularly from an evolutionary point-of-view.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The Postdoctoral Fellowship (PDF)&amp;nbsp;will, firstly, offer him the opportunity to propagate the results of his work.&amp;nbsp; He will also travel to the Max Planck Institute in Leipzig to conduct a three-month study that builds on one particular aspect of my PhD. research.&amp;nbsp; These plans will be carried out with the following in mind: that although he completed his postgraduate education in a linguistic department, the nature of his research interests (the cognition of communication; evolutionary approaches to human communication; social evolution) are such that his future career most likely lies in a psychology department.&amp;nbsp; Therefore his dissemination plans will be focused towards psychological outlets, his research project is to be conducted at a world-renowned psychology laboratory, and his mentor, Martin Pickering, is a professor of psychology. This focus will increase his appeal to psychology departments whilst allowing him to pursue his interdisciplinary research agenda.&lt;/p>

